{
	TYPE	"convo"
	DESCR	"Hammerite"
	SUB	"HM1C0311" { TEXT "Tis noted to us: The Fellahdeen are heretics and will crumble as old wood." }
	SUB	"HM1C0312" { TEXT "Thieves respect naught. Divinity--even false divinity--is as the mud below their feet. They wish not it be clay that shalt be shaped by The Builder's Hand." }
	SUB	"HM1C0313" { TEXT "Nay, our walls be cut from the thickest stones, our gates be wrought from full iron. Any who pits his strength 'gainst their strength shall smash himself with his own effort, even as the fruit falling from a tree dashes itself on a rock below." }
	SUB	"HM1C0314" { TEXT "The Builder places thy challenges before thee as a stairway of hewn stone up the tower of thine life. When thou seekest to add to those challenges, to compass thine pride, thou dost clutter the design of the stairway, and introduce cracks and weaknesses, through which The Trickster mayest enter and bring thy ruin!" }
	SUB	"HM1C0321" { TEXT "Rather to buttress our defenses." }
	SUB	"HM1C0322" { TEXT "Nay, 'tis not they who chart the building of the battle. They but put in force the will of the Baron, and the Baron chooseth not to press the attack." }
	SUB	"HM1C0323" { TEXT "Lackwit. Thinks thou the Baron wishes to defeat Blackbrook?" }
	SUB	"HM1C0324" { TEXT "How think ye? The war grants the Baron a crisis to posture before and gains him many taxes he wouldst not otherwise see." }
	SUB	"HM1C0325" { TEXT "Daah, infant! 'Tis truth. And ever so the chisel cannot know the will of the hand it serves, nor should it judge whether the mark it makes be for well or ill. 'Tis enough for a tool to be sharp and well-crafted. Only so canst it serve The Builder." }
	SUB	"HM1C0331" { TEXT "Wilt this famine never break? The Stonemarket merchants ask yet another fifth above what they charged but a month ago. Yet I think they profit little from their sales." }
	SUB	"HM1C0332" { TEXT "I would've said myself 'twas due to the war between Cyric and Bohn. The lines of battle do rage over and pass what were, times ago, farms and ranches." }
	SUB	"HM1C0333" { TEXT "Thine arguments are persuasive and do show dedication, but I think thou may simplify o'er much." }
	SUB	"HM1C0334" { TEXT "Hmm...." }
	SUB	"HM1C0351" { TEXT "Have thou learnt nothing? That name soils thy mouth." }
	SUB	"HM1C0352" { TEXT "Nay, simpleton. Knowest thou not to say 'Taffer' is to speak the name of the defeated adversary, the Trickster? 'Tis a corruption--a cloaking that acknowledges him without intent--and gives him an entry into thy thoughts." }
	SUB	"HM1C0353" { TEXT "A foe is best contested in the light, not the shadows! Allow none to so disguise themselves before thee lest thou slip into the shadows thyself, and so be lost." }
	SUB	"HM1C0601" { TEXT "In truth I have never heard such carrying on as this thief's-pawn, Cutty." }
	SUB	"HM1C0603" { TEXT "For a time I thought Block 4 might never sleep again for his coughs. But he quiets now." }
	SUB	"hm1c0701" { TEXT "(Coughs) Curse upon this dust!" }
	SUB	"hm1c0703" { TEXT "Aye, they thought stone dust would settle faster than wood. But many feet cast it up." }
	SUB	"hm1c0705" { TEXT "Tis true. And, 'til then, misfortunes are mirror for our blessings." }
	SUB	"hm1c0801" { TEXT "Hast thought upon who is likely to succeed our master?" }
	SUB	"hm1c0803" { TEXT "Art thou blind? He is old, and the Master Forgers do jostle each other for precedence." }
	SUB	"hm1c0805" { TEXT "Tis true, 'tis true...." }
	SUB	"Hm1c0902" { TEXT "Meanest thou the action on DeWall's thugs?" }
	SUB	"Hm1c0904" { TEXT "Thieves betray their own. Now as always." }
	SUB	"hm1c1002" { TEXT "The wretched man serves only the merchants in his own greed." }
	SUB	"hm1c1004" { TEXT "The Builder's truth it is, that men without belief do soften and fail, as rotten wood." }
	SUB	"hm1c1301" { TEXT "Heard thou? Tarius, seeking to save his purse, didst buy his new knife from the Shemenov's, not our smiths." }
	SUB	"hm1c1303" { TEXT "He certainly hadst fill of shame when his blade did snap at supper." }
